Day 15: Single Decision Trees - Wage Prediction [SOLUTIONS]

Your Name

2025-10-12

Self-Directed In-Class Activity (50 minutes)
Theme: Building Your First Prediction Model

Learning Objectives

By the end of this activity, you will:

  • Understand how decision trees partition the predictor space
  • Build and visualize decision trees using rpart
  • Identify the most important variables for predictions
  • Explore how tree parameters affect model complexity
  • Recognize the interpretability advantage and limitations of single trees

Scenario

You’re a data scientist for a labor economics research firm. Your task is to build an initial model that predicts hourly wages based on worker characteristics like age, education level, job type, and health insurance status.

Your boss wants: A model that’s easy to explain to policy makers and HR professionals - they need to understand WHICH factors drive wages and by how much.

Part 1: Data Exploration (10 minutes)

Before building any model, let’s understand our data!

Questions:

  • Is the wage distribution normal or skewed?
    The distribution is right-skewed with a long tail extending to high wages (max around $318.34/hour). Most workers earn in the center of the distribution.

  • Are there outliers? Should we be concerned about them?
    Yes, there are outliers at the high end (wages above $200/hour), representing about 3.3% of observations. These are legitimate high earners, not data errors, so we should keep them but be aware they may influence our model.

  • What’s a typical wage in this dataset?
    The median wage is $104.92/hour and the mean is $111.7/hour, suggesting a typical worker earns around the median value.

Part 2: Build Your First Decision Tree (10 minutes)

Task 2.1: Create Train/Test Split

# Set seed for reproducibility
set.seed(2024)

# Create a 50/50 train/test split
n <- nrow(Wage)
train_indices <- sample(1:n, size = 0.5 * n)

# Create training and test datasets
train_data <- Wage[train_indices, ]
test_data <- Wage[-train_indices, ]

# Check how many observations are in each set
cat("Training set size:", nrow(train_data), "(", 
    round(nrow(train_data)/n * 100, 1), "%)\n")
## Training set size: 1500 ( 50 %)
cat("Test set size:", nrow(test_data), "(", 
    round(nrow(test_data)/n * 100, 1), "%)\n")
## Test set size: 1500 ( 50 %)

Answer: Training set has 1500 observations (50%) and test set has 1500 observations (50%).

Task 2.2: Build a Moderate Complexity Tree

# Build a regression tree for wage
tree_model <- rpart(wage ~ age + education + jobclass + health_ins + maritl,
                    data = train_data,
                    method = "anova",
                    control = rpart.control(cp = 0.01, maxdepth = 5))

# Create a nice plot of your tree
rpart.plot(tree_model, 
           extra = 1,
           main = "Decision Tree for Wage Prediction",
           box.palette = "GnBu",
           shadow.col = "gray",
           nn = TRUE)

# How many terminal nodes (leaves) does your tree have?
num_leaves <- sum(tree_model$frame$var == "<leaf>")
cat("Number of terminal nodes (leaves):", num_leaves, "\n")
## Number of terminal nodes (leaves): 9

Questions:

  • What is the first split in the tree? Why might this be chosen first?
    The first split is on education level, specifically separating lower education levels from higher ones. This is chosen first because education creates the largest reduction in variance (RSS) - it’s the strongest predictor of wage in this dataset.

  • How many terminal nodes (leaves) does your tree have?
    The tree has 9 terminal nodes (leaves).

  • Can you trace one decision path from root to a leaf?
    Example path: Start at root → Check education level → If Advanced Degree, check age → If age is above a certain threshold, predict the highest wage tier for this combination of characteristics. The exact splits and predictions are shown in your tree plot.

Part 3: Evaluate Your Model (10 minutes)

Task 3.1: Make Predictions

# Make predictions on training data
train_predictions <- predict(tree_model, train_data)

# Make predictions on test data
test_predictions <- predict(tree_model, test_data)

Task 3.2: Calculate Performance Metrics

# Calculate training MSE
train_mse <- mean((train_data$wage - train_predictions)^2)
cat("Training MSE:", round(train_mse, 2), "\n")
## Training MSE: 1071.64
# Calculate test MSE
test_mse <- mean((test_data$wage - test_predictions)^2)
cat("Test MSE:", round(test_mse, 2), "\n")
## Test MSE: 1374.57
# Calculate training R-squared
train_rss <- sum((train_data$wage - train_predictions)^2)
train_tss <- sum((train_data$wage - mean(train_data$wage))^2)
train_r2 <- 1 - (train_rss / train_tss)
cat("Training R-squared:", round(train_r2, 4), "\n")
## Training R-squared: 0.3377
# Calculate test R-squared
test_rss <- sum((test_data$wage - test_predictions)^2)
test_tss <- sum((test_data$wage - mean(test_data$wage))^2)
test_r2 <- 1 - (test_rss / test_tss)
cat("Test R-squared:", round(test_r2, 4), "\n")
## Test R-squared: 0.2621

Questions:

  • Is there a big difference between training and test MSE? What might this indicate?
    Yes, the test MSE (1374.57) is about 28.3% higher than training MSE (1071.64), indicating some overfitting. The model performs slightly worse on unseen data, which is expected but shows the model may be memorizing training patterns rather than learning generalizable relationships.

  • What does the test MSE value mean in practical terms?
    The MSE represents the average squared error of our predictions. A test MSE of 1374.57 indicates substantial prediction errors. Given that the typical wage is around $104.92/hour, the model has moderate but not excellent predictive accuracy.

  • How well does the model explain the variation in wages based on the R² value?
    With a test R² of 0.262, the model explains only about 26.2% of the variation in wages. This means roughly 73.8% of wage variation is due to factors not captured by our model or inherent randomness. This is moderate performance - better than nothing but far from excellent.

Task 3.3: Visualize Predictions

# Create scatter plot of actual vs predicted wages on TEST data
ggplot(data.frame(actual = test_data$wage, predicted = test_predictions), 
       aes(x = actual, y = predicted)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.3, color = "blue") +
  geom_abline(slope = 1, intercept = 0, color = "red", linetype = "dashed", linewidth = 1) +
  labs(title = "Actual vs Predicted Wages (Test Set)",
       x = "Actual Wage ($/hour)",
       y = "Predicted Wage ($/hour)") +
  theme_minimal() +
  annotate("text", x = max(test_data$wage) * 0.7, y = max(test_predictions) * 0.2, 
           label = "Perfect Predictions", color = "red", size = 4)

Questions:

  • Are there systematic errors (e.g., underpredicting high wages)?
    Yes, the model systematically underpredicts high wages. High earners are predicted to earn less than they actually do. This is because decision trees predict the average value of training observations in each leaf, which pulls predictions toward the center.

  • For which wage ranges does the model perform best?
    The model performs best for wages in the middle range of the distribution, where most of the data lies. Predictions are more scattered and less accurate for very low wages and very high wages at the extremes of the distribution.

Part 4: Experiment with Tree Complexity (10 minutes)

Task 4.1: Build a Deep (Complex) Tree

# Build a very deep tree
deep_tree <- rpart(wage ~ age + education + jobclass + health_ins + maritl,
                   data = train_data,
                   method = "anova",
                   control = rpart.control(cp = 0.001, maxdepth = 10))

# Plot the deep tree
rpart.plot(deep_tree, 
           extra = 1,
           main = "Deep Decision Tree (High Complexity)",
           box.palette = "Reds")

# Calculate test MSE for deep tree
deep_predictions <- predict(deep_tree, test_data)
deep_test_mse <- mean((test_data$wage - deep_predictions)^2)
cat("Deep tree test MSE:", round(deep_test_mse, 2), "\n")
## Deep tree test MSE: 1349.77
# Calculate test R-squared for deep tree
deep_test_rss <- sum((test_data$wage - deep_predictions)^2)
deep_test_tss <- sum((test_data$wage - mean(test_data$wage))^2)
deep_test_r2 <- 1 - (deep_test_rss / deep_test_tss)
cat("Deep tree test R-squared:", round(deep_test_r2, 4), "\n")
## Deep tree test R-squared: 0.2754

# Create comparison table

  )

Questions:

  • Which tree has the best test performance?
    Looking at the comparison table above, the Deep (cp=0.001, depth=10) tree has the best test performance with the lowest test MSE of 1349.77 and highest test R² of 0.28. This represents the sweet spot between underfitting and overfitting.

  • Does the deepest tree have the best test performance? Why or why not?
    No! The deep tree has the best training performance with MSE of 914.18, but worse test performance with MSE of 1349.77 compared to the moderate tree. This is classic overfitting - the deep tree learns noise and specific patterns in the training data that don’t generalize to new data. The large difference between its training MSE (914.18) and test MSE (1349.77) shows it’s memorizing rather than learning.

  • At what age do predictions change?
    Predictions change at various split points you can see in the tree plots - typically around ages in the mid-30s, early 40s, and late 40s. These create sudden jumps in predicted wages rather than smooth transitions.

  • How realistic are these step functions?
    Not very realistic. In reality, wage probably changes gradually with age, not in sudden jumps at specific ages. The step function nature of trees means they can’t capture smooth trends, which is a significant limitation.

Task 5.3: Strengths and Weaknesses Analysis

Your Task: Write a brief report (bullet points) answering:

  1. What are the key predictors of wage according to your tree?

    • Education is the dominant predictor (you can see from the variable importance plot), with higher education levels associated with substantially higher wages
    • Age matters significantly within education groups, with experience adding meaningful value through mid-career
    • Marital status also shows importance in the model, possibly reflecting stability or other demographic factors
    • Job class and health insurance show minimal direct impact once education is accounted for

  2. What are 3 strengths of using a decision tree for this problem?

    • Interpretability: Anyone can understand the rules. The tree creates simple if-then statements that are easy to explain to HR professionals and policymakers without statistical knowledge.
    • No data preprocessing needed: The tree handles categorical variables (education, marital status) directly without dummy coding, and doesn’t require scaling or normalization.
    • Reveals interactions: The tree automatically finds that age matters more for certain education levels, capturing interaction effects without us specifying them.

  3. What are 3 limitations you observed?

    • Low predictive accuracy: The test R² of 0.262 indicates we’re explaining only about 26.2% of wage variation. The MSE values show substantial prediction errors - too imprecise for many applications.
    • Step function predictions: The model predicts only 9 distinct wage values (one per leaf), creating unrealistic jumps. Real wages change smoothly, not in large steps at exact age cutoffs.
    • High variance: When I tested with different random seeds (e.g., seed 42 or 123 instead of 2024), the tree structure changed significantly, suggesting the model is unstable and sensitive to which observations happen to be in the training set. This instability makes it unreliable.

  4. Would you recommend deploying this model? Why or why not?

    No, not for individual wage predictions. With a test R² of 0.262 and explaining only about 26.2% of wage variation, the model is too inaccurate for setting individual salaries or making hiring offers. The prediction errors are substantial and would lead to unfair salary decisions.

    However, I would recommend it for exploratory analysis and policy insights. The tree clearly shows that education is the primary wage driver (explaining substantially more variation than all other factors combined), which is valuable for workforce development policy. The interpretable rules provide actionable insights for education policy and career counseling, even if individual predictions aren’t perfectly reliable.

    For production deployment, I’d recommend this tree as a baseline that we ensemble with other models (random forests, boosting) to improve stability and accuracy while maintaining some interpretability through variable importance measures.

Reflection Questions

For Discussion or Written Response:

  1. Interpretability vs. Accuracy: Based on your tree’s R² value, is this model good enough for making policy decisions?

    Answer: It depends on the type of policy decision. The model’s test R² of 0.262 (26.2%) is insufficient for individual-level decisions like setting a specific person’s salary or determining loan eligibility. However, for aggregate policy decisions like “Should we invest more in higher education programs?” the model’s clear finding that education explains far more wage variation than any other factor is valuable and actionable. The interpretability allows policymakers to understand why the model makes its recommendations, which builds trust. For policy work, I’d prefer this transparent model showing education matters most over a black-box model with slightly better R² that policymakers can’t explain to constituents.

  2. The Variance Problem: Run your tree code with a different seed (e.g., set.seed(42) or set.seed(123)) instead of 2024. How different is the resulting tree?

    Answer: With a different seed, the tree structure changes noticeably - different split points, different variable ordering, and sometimes different numbers of leaves. While education typically remains the first split (as it’s the strongest predictor), the specific age cutoffs shift, and other variables may split at different points or in different orders. The test R² can vary by several percentage points, and specific predictions for the same individual can differ noticeably. This high variance is a fundamental problem with single trees - they’re too sensitive to the exact training sample. This is why ensemble methods like random forests, which average hundreds of trees fit to different samples, perform much better and are more stable.

  3. Missing Patterns: Look at your residual plots. What patterns do you see that the tree is missing?

    Answer: The residual plot (actual vs. predicted) shows several patterns the tree misses:

    • Underprediction of high earners: Workers earning well above average are systematically underpredicted. The tree can’t handle extreme values well because it predicts averages within leaves.
    • Overprediction of low earners: Some workers at the lower end of the wage distribution are predicted to earn more than they actually do.
    • No smooth age effect: Real wages likely increase smoothly with experience, but our tree creates discrete jumps at specific age thresholds rather than capturing gradual change.
    • Missing year/industry effects: The dataset includes year and industry information we didn’t use. Economic conditions and sector choice likely explain additional variation.
    • Can’t capture non-monotonic relationships: If wages decline after a certain age (pre-retirement effects), the tree might miss this reversal in trend or represent it poorly with step functions.

  4. Real-World Application: What ethical concerns might arise from wage prediction?

    Answer: Several serious ethical concerns:

    • Discrimination amplification: If historical wages reflect gender, race, or age discrimination, our model learns and perpetuates these biases. For example, if certain groups were historically underpaid, the model might predict lower wages for characteristics correlated with those groups.
    • Self-fulfilling prophecies: If employers use this to set wages, they might offer lower salaries to workers predicted to earn less, preventing them from ever earning more, thus reinforcing existing inequality patterns.
    • Lack of context: The model doesn’t capture individual skills, motivation, work quality, or unique circumstances. Using it for hiring or compensation decisions could unfairly disadvantage people with non-traditional backgrounds or unique qualifications.
    • Privacy concerns: Predicting wages reveals sensitive financial information and could be used for targeted advertising, price discrimination, or other purposes beyond the original intent.
    • Accountability: When the model makes substantial errors (which happens frequently given our test R² of 0.262), who’s responsible? The data scientist? The employer? The algorithm? This is a difficult question with real consequences for people’s livelihoods.
    • Limited factors: Not considering protected characteristics (race, gender) in the model means we can’t audit for discrimination, but including them could enable explicit bias. This creates a difficult ethical balance between transparency and potential misuse.

Key Takeaways

After completing this activity, you should understand:

✓ How to explore data before modeling
✓ How decision trees make predictions through binary splits
✓ How to evaluate model performance with multiple metrics
✓ How tree complexity affects overfitting
✓ The interpretability advantage of trees
✓ The high variance limitation of single trees

Main Insight: Single decision trees offer unmatched interpretability - perfect for explaining what drives outcomes to non-technical stakeholders - but suffer from modest accuracy (test R² of 0.262 or 26.2% in this problem) and high variance. They’re excellent for exploration and insight generation but need to be ensembled (random forests, boosting) for production-grade predictions. The bias-variance tradeoff and interpretability-accuracy tradeoff are fundamental in machine learning, and trees sit firmly on the interpretable/high-variance end of the spectrum.
